# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: queueing-theory-math
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The **birth–death process** (or **birth-and-death process**) is a special case of continuous-time Markov process where the state transitions are of only two types: "births", which increase the state variable by one and "deaths", which decrease the state by one.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The model's name comes from a common application, the use of such models to represent the current size of a population where the transitions are literal births and deaths.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Birth–death processes have many applications in demography, queueing theory, performance engineering, epidemiology, biology and other areas.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] They may be used, for example, to study the evolution of bacteria, the number of people with a disease within a population, or the number of customers in line at the supermarket.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] When a birth occurs, the process goes from state *n* to *n* + 1.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] When a death occurs, the process goes from state *n* to state *n* − 1.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The process is specified by positive birth rates $\{\lambda _{i}\}_{i=0\dots \infty }$ and positive death rates $\{\mu _{i}\}_{i=1\dots \infty }$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The number of individuals in the process at time t is denoted by $X(t)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The process has the Markov property and $P_{i,j}(t)={\mathsf {P}}\{X(t+s)=j|X(s)=i\}$ describes how $X(t)$ changes through time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] This process is represented by the following figure with the states of the process (i.e. the number of individuals in the population) depicted by the circles, and transitions between states indicated by the arrows.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] For recurrence and transience in Markov processes see Section 5.3 from Markov chain.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Conditions for recurrence and transience were established by Samuel Karlin and James McGregor.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] By using the **extended Bertrand's test**, the conditions for recurrence, transience, ergodicity and null-recurrence can be derived in a more explicit form.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Then, the conditions for recurrence and transience of a birth-and-death process are as follows.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] where the empty sum for $K=1$ is assumed to be 0.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Wider classes of birth-and-death processes, for which the conditions for recurrence and transience can be established, can be found in.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Consider one-dimensional random walk $S_{t},\ t=0,1,\ldots ,$ that is defined as follows.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] So, recurrence or transience of the random walk is associated with recurrence or transience of the birth-and-death process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] where the empty sum for $K=1$ is assumed to be zero.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] In turn, the last system of differential equations is derived from the system of difference equations that describes the dynamic of the system in a small time $\Delta t$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] During this small time $\Delta t$ only three types of transitions are considered as one death, or one birth, or no birth nor death.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The probability of the first two of these transitions has the order of $\Delta t$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Other transitions during this small interval $\Delta t$ such as *more than one birth*, or *more than one death*, or *at least one birth and at least one death* have the probabilities that are of smaller order than $\Delta t$ , and hence are negligible in derivations.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] If the system is in state *k*, then the probability of birth during an interval $\Delta t$ is $\lambda _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ , the probability of death is $\mu _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ , and the probability of no birth and no death is $1-\lambda _{k}\Delta t-\mu _{k}\Delta t+o(\Delta t)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] For a population process, "birth" is the transition towards increasing the population size by 1 while "death" is the transition towards decreasing the population size by 1.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] A pure birth process is a birth–death process where $\mu _{i}=0$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] A **pure death process** is a birth–death process where $\lambda _{i}=0$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Birth–death processes are used in phylodynamics as a prior distribution for phylogenies, i.e. a binary tree in which birth events correspond to branches of the tree and death events correspond to leaf nodes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Notably, they are used in viral phylodynamics to understand the transmission process and how the number of people infected changes through time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The use of generalized birth-death processes in phylodynamics has stimulated investigations into the degree to which the rates of birth and death can be identified from data.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] While the model is unidentifiable in general, the subset of models that are typically used are identifiable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] In queueing theory the birth–death process is the most fundamental example of a queueing model, the *M/M/C/K/ $\infty$ /FIFO* (in complete Kendall's notation) queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] This is a queue with Poisson arrivals, drawn from an infinite population, and *C* servers with exponentially distributed service times with *K* places in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Despite the assumption of an infinite population this model is a good model for various telecommunication systems.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The **M/M/1** is a single server queue with an infinite buffer size.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] In a non-random environment the birth–death process in queueing models tend to be long-term averages, so the average rate of arrival is given as $\lambda$ and the average service time as $1/\mu$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Pure birth process with $\lambda _{k}\equiv \lambda$ is a particular case of the M/M/1 queueing process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] That is, a (homogeneous) Poisson process is a pure birth process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The M/M/C is a multi-server queue with *C* servers and an infinite buffer.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Pure death process with $\mu _{k}=k\mu$ is a particular case of the M/M/C queueing process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] that presents the version of binomial distribution depending on time parameter t (see Binomial process).
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The M/M/1/K queue is a single server queue with a buffer of size *K*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] This queue has applications in telecommunications, as well as in biology when a population has a capacity limit.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] A queue is said to be in equilibrium if the steady state probabilities $\pi _{k}=\lim _{t\to \infty }p_{k}(t),\ k=0,1,\ldots ,$ exist.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The condition for the existence of these steady-state probabilities in the case of M/M/1 queue is $\rho =\lambda /\mu <1$ and in the case of M/M/C queue is $\rho =\lambda /(C\mu )<1$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The parameter $\rho$ is usually called load parameter or utilization parameter.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Sometimes it is also called traffic intensity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] Bilateral birth-and-death process is defined similarly to that standard one with the only difference that the birth and death rates $\lambda _{i}$ and $\mu _{i}$ are defined for the values of index parameter $i=0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\ldots$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/birth-death-process] The notions of ergodicity and null-recurrence are defined similarly by extending the corresponding notions of the standard birth-and-death process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] In queueing theory, a discipline within the mathematical theory of probability, **Kendall's notation** (or sometimes **Kendall notation**) is the standard system used to describe and classify a queueing node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] Kendall proposed describing queueing models using three factors written A/S/*c* in 1953 where A denotes the time between arrivals to the queue, S the service time distribution and *c* the number of service channels open at the node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] It has since been extended to A/S/*c*/*K*/*N*/D where *K* is the capacity of the queue, *N* is the size of the population of jobs to be served, and D is the queueing discipline.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] When the final three parameters are not specified (e.g.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] M/M/1 queue), it is assumed *K* = ∞, *N* = ∞ and D = FIFO.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] A M/M/1 queue means that the time between arrivals is Markovian (M), i.e. the inter-arrival time follows an exponential distribution of parameter λ.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The second M means that the service time is Markovian: it follows an exponential distribution of parameter μ.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The last parameter is the number of service channel, which is one (1).
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] In this section, we describe the parameters A/S/*c*/*K*/*N*/D from left to right.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] This gives the distribution of time of the service of a customer.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The number of service channels (or servers).
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The M/M/1 queue has a single server and the M/M/c queue *c* servers.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The capacity of queue, or the maximum number of customers allowed in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] When the number is at this maximum, further arrivals are turned away.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] If this number is omitted, the capacity is assumed to be unlimited, or infinite.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] The size of the population from which the customers come.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] A small population will significantly affect the effective arrival rate, because, as more customers are in system, there are fewer free customers available to arrive into the system.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] If this number is omitted, the population is assumed to be unlimited, or infinite.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] : An alternative notation practice is to record the queue discipline before the population and system capacity, with or without enclosing parenthesis.
[src:queueing-theory-math/kendall-s-notation] This does not normally cause confusion because the notation is different.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The relationship is not influenced by the arrival process distribution, the service distribution, the service order, or practically anything else.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] In most queuing systems, service time is the bottleneck that creates the queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The result applies to any system, and particularly, it applies to systems within systems.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] For example in a bank branch, the customer line might be one subsystem, and each of the tellers another subsystem, and Little's result could be applied to each one, as well as the whole thing.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The only requirement is that the system be ergodic.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] In some cases it is possible not only to mathematically relate the *average* number in the system to the *average* wait but even to relate the entire *probability distribution* (and moments) of the number in the system to the wait.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] In a 1954 paper, Little's law was assumed true and used without proof.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The form *L* = *λW* was first published by Philip M.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Morse where he challenged readers to find a situation where the relationship did not hold.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Little published in 1961 his proof of the law, showing that no such situation existed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Little's proof was followed by a simpler version by Jewell and another by Eilon.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Shaler Stidham published a different and more intuitive proof in 1972.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Imagine an application that had no easy way to measure response time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] For example: A queue depth meter shows an average of nine jobs waiting to be serviced.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Add one for the job being serviced, so there is an average of ten jobs in the system.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Another meter shows a mean throughput of 50 per second.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The mean response time is calculated as 0.2 seconds = 10 / 50 per second.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Imagine a small store with a single counter and an area for browsing, where only one person can be at the counter at a time, and no one leaves without buying something.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] If the rate at which people enter the store (called the arrival rate) is the rate at which they exit (called the exit rate), the system is stable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] By contrast, an arrival rate exceeding an exit rate would represent an unstable system, where the number of waiting customers in the store would gradually increase towards infinity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Assume customers arrive at the rate of 10 per hour and stay an average of 0.5 hour.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] This means we should find the average number of customers in the store at any time to be 5.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Now suppose the store is considering doing more advertising to raise the arrival rate to 20 per hour.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The store must either be prepared to host an average of 10 occupants or must reduce the time each customer spends in the store to 0.25 hour.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The store might achieve the latter by ringing up the bill faster or by adding more counters.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] We can apply Little's Law to systems within the store.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] For example, consider the counter and its queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Assume we notice that there are on average 2 customers in the queue and at the counter.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] We know the arrival rate is 10 per hour, so customers must be spending 0.2 hours on average checking out.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] We can even apply Little's Law to the counter itself.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The average number of people at the counter would be in the range (0, 1) since no more than one person can be at the counter at a time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] In that case, the average number of people at the counter is also known as the utilisation of the counter.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] However, because a store in reality generally has a limited amount of space, it can eventually become unstable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] If the arrival rate is much greater than the exit rate, the store will eventually start to overflow, and thus any new arriving customers will simply be rejected (and forced to go somewhere else or try again later) until there is once again free space available in the store.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] This is also the difference between the *arrival rate* and the *effective arrival rate*, where the arrival rate roughly corresponds to the rate at which customers arrive at the store, whereas the effective arrival rate corresponds to the rate at which customers *enter* the store.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] However, in a system with an infinite size and no loss, the two are equal.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Little's law is widely used in manufacturing to predict lead time based on the production rate and the amount of work-in-process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Software-performance testers have used Little's law to ensure that the observed performance results are not due to bottlenecks imposed by the testing apparatus.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Other applications include staffing emergency departments in hospitals.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] Lastly, an equivalent version of Little's law also applies in the fields of demography and population biology, although not referred to as "Little's Law".
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] For example, Cohen (2008) explains that in a homogeneous stationary population without migration, $P=B\times e$ , where P is the total population size, B is the number of births per year, and e is the life expectancy from birth.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] The formula $P=B\times e$ is thus directly equivalent to Little's law ( $L=\lambda \times W$ ).
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] However, biological populations tend to be dynamic and therefore more complicated to model accurately.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] In some cases, it is possible not only to relate averages but to relate the entire probability distribution of the number in the system to the time in the system under a first come, first served discipline.
[src:queueing-theory-math/little-s-law] A distributional relation for many FIFO/Poisson-class systems was derived by Keilson and Servi (1988) and further developed in related work, including links to the Fuhrmann–Cooper decomposition; later, Bertsimas and Nakazato (1995) provided a new proof and surveyed applications.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] In queueing theory, a discipline within the mathematical theory of probability, an **M/M/1 queue** represents the queue length in a system having a single server, where arrivals are determined by a Poisson process and job service times have an exponential distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The model name is written in Kendall's notation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The model is the most elementary of queueing models and an attractive object of study as closed-form expressions can be obtained for many metrics of interest in this model.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] An extension of this model with more than one server is the M/M/c queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] An M/M/1 queue is a stochastic process whose state space is the set {0,1,2,3,...} where the value corresponds to the number of customers in the system, including any currently in service.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] This is the same continuous time Markov chain as in a birth–death process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The state space diagram for this chain is as below.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The model is considered stable only if λ < μ.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] If, on average, arrivals happen faster than service completions the queue will grow indefinitely long and the system will not have a stationary distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The stationary distribution is the limiting distribution for large values of *t*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] Various performance measures can be computed explicitly for the M/M/1 queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] We write ρ = λ/μ for the utilization of the buffer and require ρ < 1 for the queue to be stable. ρ represents the average proportion of time which the server is occupied.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] We see that the number of customers in the system is geometrically distributed with parameter 1 − *ρ*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] Thus the average number of customers in the system is *ρ*/(1 − *ρ*) and the variance of number of customers in the system is *ρ*/(1 − *ρ*)2.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] This result holds for any work conserving service regime, such as processor sharing.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The busy period is the time period measured between the instant a customer arrives to an empty system until the instant a customer departs leaving behind an empty system.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] where *I*1 is a modified Bessel function of the first kind, obtained by using Laplace transforms and inverting the solution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The average response time or sojourn time (total time a customer spends in the system) does not depend on scheduling discipline and can be computed using Little's law as 1/(*μ* − *λ*).
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The distribution of response times experienced does depend on scheduling discipline.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] In an M/M/1-PS queue there is no waiting line and all jobs receive an equal proportion of the service capacity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] Suppose the single server serves at rate 16 and there are 4 jobs in the system, each job will experience service at rate 4.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The rate at which jobs receive service changes each time a job arrives at or departs from the system.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] For customers who arrive to find the queue as a stationary process, the Laplace transform of the distribution of response times experienced by customers was published in 1970, for which an integral representation is known.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] The mean response time for a job arriving and requiring amount *x* of service can therefore be computed as *x μ*/(*μ* − *λ*).
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] An alternative approach computes the same results using a spectral expansion method.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] We can write a probability mass function dependent on *t* to describe the probability that the M/M/1 queue is in a particular state at a given time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] We assume that the queue is initially in state *i* and write *p**k*(*t*) for the probability of being in state *k* at time *t*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] where i is the initial number of customers in the station at time $t=0$ , $\rho =\lambda /\mu$ , $a=2{\sqrt {\lambda \mu }}$ and $I_{k}$ is the modified Bessel function of the first kind.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] Moments for the transient solution can be expressed as the sum of two monotone functions.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] When the utilization *ρ* is close to 1 the process can be approximated by a reflected Brownian motion with drift parameter *λ* – *μ* and variance parameter *λ* + *μ*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/m-1-queue] This heavy traffic limit was first introduced by John Kingman.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The process's name derives from the fact that the number of points in any given finite region follows a Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The process and the distribution are named after French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The process itself was discovered independently and repeatedly in several settings, including experiments on radioactive decay, telephone call arrivals and actuarial science.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is used as a mathematical model for seemingly random processes in numerous disciplines including astronomy, biology, ecology, geology, seismology, physics, economics, image processing, and telecommunications.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson point process is often defined on the real number line, where it can be viewed as a stochastic process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It is used, for example, in queueing theory to model random events distributed in time, such as the arrival of customers at a store, phone calls at an telephone exchange, or the occurrence of earthquakes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the point process—also known as a **spatial Poisson process**—can represent the locations of scattered objects such as transmitters in a wireless network, particles colliding into a particle detector, or trees in a forest.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The process is widely used in mathematical models and in related fields, including spatial point processes, stochastic geometry, spatial statistics and continuum percolation theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The point process depends on a single mathematical object, which, depending on the context, may be a constant, a locally integrable function or, in more general settings, a Radon measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the first case, the constant, known as the **rate** or **intensity**, is the average density of the points in the Poisson process located in some region of space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The resulting point process is called a **homogeneous** or **stationary Poisson point process**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the second case, the point process is called an **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process**, and the average density of points depend on the location of the underlying space of the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The word *point* is often omitted, but there are other *Poisson processes* of objects, which, instead of points, consist of more complicated mathematical objects such as lines and polygons, and such processes can be based on the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Both the homogeneous and nonhomogeneous Poisson point processes are particular cases of the generalized renewal process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Depending on the setting, the process has several equivalent definitions as well as definitions of varying generality owing to its many applications and characterizations.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Consequently, the notation, terminology and level of mathematical rigour used to define and study the Poisson point process and points processes in general vary according to the context.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite all this, the Poisson point process has two key properties—the Poisson property and the independence property— that play an essential role in all settings where the Poisson point process is used.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The two properties are not logically independent; indeed, the Poisson distribution of point counts implies the independence property, while in the converse direction the assumptions that: (i) the point process is simple, (ii) has no fixed atoms, and (iii) is a.s. boundedly finite are required.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A Poisson point process is characterized via the Poisson distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle n!}$ denotes factorial and the parameter ${\textstyle \Lambda }$ determines the shape of the distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, a Poisson point process has the property that the number of points in a bounded region of the process's underlying space is a Poisson-distributed random variable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Consider a collection of disjoint and bounded subregions of the underlying space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, the number of points of a Poisson point process in each bounded subregion will be completely independent of all the others.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This property is known under several names such as *complete randomness*, *complete independence*, or *independent scattering* and is common to all Poisson point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, there is a lack of interaction between different regions and the points in general, which motivates the Poisson process being sometimes called a *purely* or *completely* random process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter, called **rate** or **intensity**, is related to the expected (or average) number of Poisson points existing in some bounded region, where *rate* is usually used when the underlying space has one dimension.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ can be interpreted as the average number of points per some unit of extent such as length, area, volume, or time, depending on the underlying mathematical space, and it is also called the *mean density* or *mean rate*; see Terminology.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, can be defined as a counting process, a type of stochastic process, which can be denoted as ${\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A counting process represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time ${\textstyle t}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson counting process can also be defined by stating that the time differences between events of the counting process are exponential variables with mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The time differences between the events or arrivals are known as **interarrival** or **interoccurrence** times.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Interpreted as a point process, a Poisson point process can be defined on the real line by considering the number of points of the process in the interval ${\textstyle (a,b]}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, ${\textstyle N(a,b]}$ is a Poisson random variable with mean ${\textstyle \lambda (b-a)}$ , where ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the number of points in any two disjoint intervals, say, ${\textstyle (a_{1},b_{1}]}$ and ${\textstyle (a_{2},b_{2}]}$ are independent of each other, and this extends to any finite number of disjoint intervals.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the queueing theory context, one can consider a point existing (in an interval) as an *event*, but this is different to the word event in the probability theory sense.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It follows that ${\textstyle \lambda }$ is the expected number of *arrivals* that occur per unit of time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, for any finite ${\textstyle t>0}$ , the random variable ${\textstyle N(a+t,b+t]}$ is independent of ${\textstyle t}$ , so it is also called a stationary Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\operatorname {E}$ denotes the expectation operator.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ of the Poisson process coincides with the *density* of points.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous Poisson point process adheres to its own form of the (strong) law of large numbers.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle \lim }$ denotes the limit of a function, and $\lambda$ is expected number of arrivals occurred per unit of time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The distance between two consecutive points of a point process on the real line will be an exponential random variable with parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ (or equivalently, mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ ).
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A point process is called a **simple point process** when the probability of any of its two points coinciding in the same position, on the underlying space, is zero.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For point processes in general on the real line, the property of orderliness implies that the process is simple, which is the case for the homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the Poisson process is a type of continuous-time Markov process known as a birth process, a special case of the birth–death process (with just births and zero deaths).
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] More complicated processes with the Markov property, such as Markov arrival processes, have been defined where the Poisson process is a special case.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous Poisson process is considered just on the half-line ${\textstyle [0,\infty )}$ , which can be the case when ${\textstyle t}$ represents time then the resulting process is not truly invariant under translation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In that case the Poisson process is no longer stationary, according to some definitions of stationarity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] There have been many applications of the homogeneous Poisson process on the real line in an attempt to model seemingly random and independent events occurring.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It has a fundamental role in queueing theory, which is the probability field of developing suitable stochastic models to represent the random arrival and departure of certain phenomena.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, customers arriving and being served or phone calls arriving at a phone exchange can be both studied with techniques from queueing theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson process on the real line is considered one of the simplest stochastic processes for counting random numbers of points.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This process can be generalized in a number of ways.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] One possible generalization is to extend the distribution of interarrival times from the exponential distribution to other distributions, which introduces the stochastic process known as a renewal process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Another generalization is to define the Poisson point process on higher dimensional spaces such as the plane.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A **spatial Poisson process** is a Poisson point process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For its mathematical definition, one first considers a bounded, open or closed (or more precisely, Borel measurable) region ${\textstyle B}$ of the plane.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of a point process $\textstyle N$ existing in this region $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is a random variable, denoted by $\textstyle N(B)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ denotes the area of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For some finite integer $\textstyle k\geq 1$ , we can give the finite-dimensional distribution of the homogeneous Poisson point process by first considering a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel (measurable) sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of the point process $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ can be written as $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The spatial Poisson point process features prominently in spatial statistics, stochastic geometry, and continuum percolation theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is applied in various physical sciences such as a model developed for alpha particles being detected.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In recent years, it has been frequently used to model seemingly disordered spatial configurations of certain wireless communication networks.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, models for cellular or mobile phone networks have been developed where it is assumed the phone network transmitters, known as base stations, are positioned according to a homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The previous homogeneous Poisson point process immediately extends to higher dimensions by replacing the notion of area with (high dimensional) volume.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ now denotes the $\textstyle d$ -dimensional volume of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, for a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , let $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ denote the number of points of $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Homogeneous Poisson point processes do not depend on the position of the underlying space through its parameter $\textstyle \lambda$ , which implies it is both a stationary process (invariant to translation) and an isotropic (invariant to rotation) stochastic process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Similarly to the one-dimensional case, the homogeneous point process is restricted to some bounded subset of ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ , then depending on some definitions of stationarity, the process is no longer stationary.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous point process is defined on the real line as a mathematical model for occurrences of some phenomenon, then it has the characteristic that the positions of these occurrences or events on the real line (often interpreted as time) will be uniformly distributed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, if an event occurs (according to this process) in an interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , then its location will be a uniform random variable defined on that interval.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous point process is sometimes called the *uniform* Poisson point process (see Terminology).
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This uniformity property extends to higher dimensions in the Cartesian coordinate, but not in, for example, polar coordinates.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process** (see Terminology) is a Poisson point process with a Poisson parameter set as some location-dependent function in the underlying space on which the Poisson process is defined.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the inhomogeneous or non-homogeneous Poisson point process has mean measure given by a one-dimensional integral.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For two real numbers $\textstyle a$ and $\textstyle b$ , where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , denote by $\textstyle N(a,b]$ the number points of an inhomogeneous Poisson process with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (t)$ occurring in the interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] which means that the random variable $\textstyle N(a,b]$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \operatorname {E} [N(a,b]]=\Lambda (a,b)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A feature of the one-dimension setting, is that an inhomogeneous Poisson process can be transformed into a homogeneous by a monotone transformation or mapping, which is achieved with the inverse of $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, is also sometimes defined as a counting process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] With this interpretation, the process, which is sometimes written as $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ , represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time $\textstyle t$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle o(h)$ is asymptotic or little-o notation for $\textstyle o(h)/h\rightarrow 0$ as $\textstyle h\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the case of point processes with refractoriness (e.g., neural spike trains) a stronger version of property 4 applies: $\Pr\{N(t+h)-N(t)\geq 2\}=o(h^{2})$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] An inhomogeneous Poisson process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is called a **spatial Poisson process** It is defined with intensity function and its intensity measure is obtained performing a surface integral of its intensity function over some region.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle B}$ is some bounded region in the plane ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, ${\textstyle \Lambda (B)}$ corresponds to a surface integral while in ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ the integral becomes a ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume integral.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] When the real line is interpreted as time, the inhomogeneous process is used in the fields of counting processes and in queueing theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the Poisson point process is important in the related disciplines of stochastic geometry and spatial statistics.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The intensity measure of this point process is dependent on the location of underlying space, which means it can be used to model phenomena with a density that varies over some region.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the phenomena can be represented as points that have a location-dependent density.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This processes has been used in various disciplines and uses include the study of salmon and sea lice in the oceans, forestry, and search problems.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, given a homogeneous Poisson point process on the real line, the probability of finding a single point of the process in a small interval of width ${\textstyle \delta }$ is approximately ${\textstyle \lambda \delta }$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In fact, such intuition is how the Poisson point process is sometimes introduced and its distribution derived.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If a Poisson point process has an intensity measure that is a locally finite and diffuse (or non-atomic), then it is a **simple point process**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For a simple point process, the probability of a point existing at a single point or location in the underlying (state) space is either zero or one.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This implies that, with probability one, no two (or more) points of a Poisson point process coincide in location in the underlying space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Simulating a Poisson point process on a computer is usually done in a bounded region of space, known as a simulation *window*, and requires two steps: appropriately creating a random number of points and then suitably placing the points in a random manner.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Both these two steps depend on the specific Poisson point process that is being simulated.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points ${\textstyle N}$ in the window, denoted here by ${\textstyle W}$ , needs to be simulated, which is done by using a (pseudo)-random number generating function capable of simulating Poisson random variables.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case with the constant ${\textstyle \lambda }$ , the mean of the Poisson random variable ${\textstyle N}$ is set to ${\textstyle \lambda |W|}$ where ${\textstyle |W|}$ is the length, area or ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume of ${\textstyle W}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The second stage requires randomly placing the $\textstyle N$ points in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case in one dimension, all points are uniformly and independently placed in the window or interval $\textstyle W$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For higher dimensions in a Cartesian coordinate system, each coordinate is uniformly and independently placed in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If the window is not a subspace of Cartesian space (for example, inside a unit sphere or on the surface of a unit sphere), then the points will not be uniformly placed in $\textstyle W$ , and suitable change of coordinates (from Cartesian) are needed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For the inhomogeneous case, a couple of different methods can be used depending on the nature of the intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity function is sufficiently simple, then independent and random non-uniform (Cartesian or other) coordinates of the points can be generated.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For more complicated intensity functions, one can use an acceptance-rejection method, which consists of using (or 'accepting') only certain random points and not using (or 'rejecting') the other points, based on the ratio:.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle x_{i}$ is the point under consideration for acceptance or rejection.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In measure theory, the Poisson point process can be further generalized to what is sometimes known as the **general Poisson point process** or **general Poisson process** by using a Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ , which is a locally finite measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In general, this Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ can be atomic, which means multiple points of the Poisson point process can exist in the same location of the underlying space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In this situation, the number of points at $\textstyle x$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \Lambda ({x})$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] But sometimes the converse is assumed, so the Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is diffuse or non-atomic.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where the density $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ is known, among other terms, as the intensity function.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite its name, the Poisson point process was neither discovered nor studied by its namesake.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It is cited as an example of Stigler's law of eponymy.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The name arises from the process's inherent relation to the Poisson distribution, derived by Poisson as a limiting case of the binomial distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It describes the probability of the sum of $\textstyle n$ Bernoulli trials with probability $\textstyle p$ , often likened to the number of heads (or tails) after $\textstyle n$ biased coin flips with the probability of a head (or tail) occurring being $\textstyle p$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For some positive constant $\textstyle \Lambda >0$ , as $\textstyle n$ increases towards infinity and $\textstyle p$ decreases towards zero such that the product $\textstyle np=\Lambda$ is fixed, the Poisson distribution more closely approximates that of the binomial.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1841, Poisson derived the Poisson distribution by studying the binomial distribution in the limit as $\textstyle p$ goes to zero and $\textstyle n$ goes to infinity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The distribution appears only once in Poisson's work, and the result was not well known during his time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Over the following years, others used the distribution without citing Poisson, including Philipp Ludwig von Seidel and Ernst Abbe.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] At the end of the 19th century, Ladislaus Bortkiewicz revived interest in the distribution by citing Poisson and using real data on the number of deaths from horse kicks in the Prussian army.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] There are a number of claims for early uses or discoveries of the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] This work inspired Simon Newcomb to study the problem and to calculate the Poisson distribution as an approximation for the binomial distribution in 1860.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] At the beginning of the 20th century the Poisson process (in one dimension) would arise independently in different situations.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In Sweden 1903, Filip Lundberg published a thesis containing work, now considered fundamental and pioneering, where he proposed to model insurance claims with a homogeneous Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang derived the Poisson distribution in 1909 when developing a mathematical model for the number of incoming phone calls in a finite time interval.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang unaware of Poisson's earlier work and assumed that the number phone calls arriving in each interval of time were independent of each other.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] He then found the limiting case, which is effectively recasting the Poisson distribution as a limit of the binomial distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1910 Ernest Rutherford and Hans Geiger published experimental results on counting alpha particles.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Their experimental work had mathematical contributions from Harry Bateman, who derived Poisson probabilities as a solution to a family of differential equations, though the solution had been derived earlier, resulting in the independent discovery of the Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] After this time, there were many studies and applications of the Poisson process, but its early history is complicated, which has been explained by the various applications of the process in numerous fields by biologists, ecologists, engineers and various physical scientists.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The early results were published in different languages and in different settings, with no standard terminology and notation used.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, in 1922 Swedish chemist and Nobel Laureate Theodor Svedberg proposed a model in which a spatial Poisson point process is the underlying process to study how plants are distributed in plant communities.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] A number of mathematicians started studying the process in the early 1930s, and important contributions were made by Andrey Kolmogorov, William Feller and Aleksandr Khinchin, among others.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the field of teletraffic engineering, mathematicians and statisticians studied and used Poisson and other point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The Swede Conny Palm in his 1943 dissertation studied the Poisson and other point processes in the one-dimensional setting by examining them in terms of the statistical or stochastic dependence between the points in time.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In his work exists the first known recorded use of the term *point processes* as *Punktprozesse* in German.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It is believed that William Feller was the first in print to refer to it as the *Poisson process* in a 1940 paper.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Although the Swede Ove Lundberg used the term *Poisson process* in his 1940 PhD dissertation, in which Feller was acknowledged as an influence, it has been claimed that Feller coined the term before 1940.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It has been remarked that both Feller and Lundberg used the term as though it were well-known, implying it was already in spoken use by then.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The terminology of point process theory in general has been criticized for being too varied.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In addition to the word *point* often being omitted, the homogeneous Poisson (point) process is also called a *stationary* Poisson (point) process, as well as *uniform* Poisson (point) process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, as well as being called *nonhomogeneous*, is also referred to as the *non-stationary* Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The term *point process* has been criticized, as the term *process* can suggest over time and space, so *random point field*, resulting in the terms *Poisson random point field* or *Poisson point field* being also used.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The underlying mathematical space of the Poisson point process is called a **carrier space**, or **state space**, though the latter term has a different meaning in the context of stochastic processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the context of point processes, the term "state space" can mean the space on which the point process is defined such as the real line, which corresponds to the index set or parameter set in stochastic process terminology.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is called the *intensity measure*, *mean measure*, or *parameter measure*, as there are no standard terms.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If $\textstyle \Lambda$ has a derivative or density, denoted by $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ , is called the *intensity function* of the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous Poisson point process, the derivative of the intensity measure is simply a constant $\textstyle \lambda >0$ , which can be referred to as the *rate*, usually when the underlying space is the real line, or the *intensity*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] It is also called the *mean rate* or the *mean density* or *rate*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For $\textstyle \lambda =1$ , the corresponding process is sometimes referred to as the *standard Poisson* (point) process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The extent of the Poisson point process is sometimes called the *exposure*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The notation of the Poisson point process depends on its setting and the field it is being applied in.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, on the real line, the Poisson process, both homogeneous or inhomogeneous, is sometimes interpreted as a counting process, and the notation $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ is used to represent the Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Another reason for varying notation is due to the theory of point processes, which has a couple of mathematical interpretations.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, a simple Poisson point process may be considered as a random set, which suggests the notation $\textstyle x\in N$ , implying that $\textstyle x$ is a random point belonging to or being an element of the Poisson point process $\textstyle N$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] These different interpretations results in notation being used from mathematical fields such as measure theory and set theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the set theory and integral or measure theory notation can be used interchangeably.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] demonstrates two different ways to write a summation over a point process (see also Campbell's theorem (probability)).
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, the integral notation on the left-hand side is interpreting the point process as a random counting measure while the sum on the right-hand side suggests a random set interpretation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In probability theory, operations are applied to random variables for different purposes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Sometimes these operations are regular expectations that produce the average or variance of a random variable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Others, such as characteristic functions (or Laplace transforms) of a random variable can be used to uniquely identify or characterize random variables and prove results like the central limit theorem.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In the theory of point processes there exist analogous mathematical tools which usually exist in the forms of measures and functionals instead of moments and functions respectively.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] One version of Campbell's theorem involves the Laplace functional of the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The probability generating function of non-negative integer-valued random variable leads to the probability generating functional being defined analogously with respect to any non-negative bounded function $\textstyle v$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ such that $\textstyle 0\leq v(x)\leq 1$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where the product is performed for all the points in ${\textstyle N}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ of $\textstyle {N}$ is locally finite, then the ${\textstyle G}$ is well-defined for any measurable function $\textstyle u$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ is the length, area or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The Mecke equation characterizes the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Let $\mathbb {N} _{\sigma }$ be the space of all $\sigma$ -finite measures on some general space ${\mathcal {Q}}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B_{i}|$ is the length, area, or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] Simple point processes are completely characterized by their void probabilities.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, complete information of a simple point process is captured entirely in its void probabilities, and two simple point processes have the same void probabilities if and if only if they are the same point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] The case for Poisson process is sometimes known as **Rényi’s theorem**, which is named after Alfréd Rényi who discovered the result for the case of a homogeneous point process in one dimension.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p01] then $\textstyle N$ is a Poisson point process with intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Mathematical operations can be performed on point processes to get new point processes and develop new mathematical models for the locations of certain objects.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] One example of an operation is known as thinning which entails deleting or removing the points of some point process according to a rule, creating a new process with the remaining points (the deleted points also form a point process).
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] For the Poisson process, the independent $\textstyle p(x)$ -thinning operations results in another Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] This thinning result of the Poisson point process is sometimes known as **Prekopa's theorem**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The two separate Poisson point processes formed respectively from the removed and kept points are stochastically independent of each other.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, if a region is known to contain $\textstyle n$ kept points (from the original Poisson point process), then this will have no influence on the random number of removed points in the same region.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] This ability to randomly create two independent Poisson point processes from one is sometimes known as *splitting* the Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, any points located in any of the point processes $\textstyle N_{1},N_{2}\dots$ will also be located in the superposition of these point processes $\textstyle {N}$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, the union of two (or countably more) Poisson processes is another Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The operation clustering is performed when each point $\textstyle x$ of some point process $\textstyle {N}$ is replaced by another (possibly different) point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If the original process $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the resulting process $\textstyle {N}_{c}$ is called a Poisson cluster point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] A mathematical model may require randomly moving points of a point process to other locations on the underlying mathematical space, which gives rise to a point process operation known as displacement or translation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] One version of the displacement theorem involves a Poisson point process $\textstyle {N}$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, after each random and independent displacement of points, the original Poisson point process still exists.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The displacement theorem can be extended such that the Poisson points are randomly displaced from one Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ to another Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d'}$ , where $\textstyle d'\geq 1$ is not necessarily equal to $\textstyle d$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Another property that is considered useful is the ability to map a Poisson point process from one underlying space to another space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If the mapping (or transformation) adheres to some conditions, then the resulting mapped (or transformed) collection of points also form a Poisson point process, and this result is sometimes referred to as the **mapping theorem**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The theorem involves some Poisson point process with mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ on some underlying space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If the locations of the points are mapped (that is, the point process is transformed) according to some function to another underlying space, then the resulting point process is also a Poisson point process but with a different mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] with no atoms, where $\textstyle B$ is a Borel set and $\textstyle f^{-1}$ denotes the inverse of the function $\textstyle f$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the new process $\textstyle {N}'$ is also a Poisson point process with the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The tractability of the Poisson process means that sometimes it is convenient to approximate a non-Poisson point process with a Poisson one.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The overall aim is to approximate both the number of points of some point process and the location of each point by a Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] There a number of methods that can be used to justify, informally or rigorously, approximating the occurrence of random events or phenomena with suitable Poisson point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The more rigorous methods involve deriving upper bounds on the probability metrics between the Poisson and non-Poisson point processes, while other methods can be justified by less formal heuristics.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] One method for approximating random events or phenomena with Poisson processes is called the **clumping heuristic**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The general heuristic or principle involves using the Poisson point process (or Poisson distribution) to approximate events, which are considered rare or unlikely, of some stochastic process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In some cases these rare events are close to being independent, hence a Poisson point process can be used.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method is a mathematical technique originally developed for approximating random variables such as Gaussian and Poisson variables, which has also been applied to point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method can be used to derive upper bounds on probability metrics, which give way to quantify how different two random mathematical objects vary stochastically.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Upperbounds on probability metrics such as total variation and Wasserstein distance have been derived.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Researchers have applied Stein's method to Poisson point processes in a number of ways, such as using Palm calculus.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Techniques based on Stein's method have been developed to factor into the upper bounds the effects of certain point process operations such as thinning and superposition.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method has also been used to derive upper bounds on metrics of Poisson and other processes such as the Cox point process, which is a Poisson process with a random intensity measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, when an operation is applied to a general point process the resulting process is usually not a Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if a point process, other than a Poisson, has its points randomly and independently displaced, then the process would not necessarily be a Poisson point process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Such convergence work is directly related to the results known as the Palm–Khinchin equations, which has its origins in the work of Conny Palm and Aleksandr Khinchin, and help explains why the Poisson process can often be used as a mathematical model of various random phenomena.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson point process can be generalized by, for example, changing its intensity measure or defining on more general mathematical spaces.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] These generalizations can be studied mathematically as well as used to mathematically model or represent physical phenomena.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson-type random measures (PT) are a family of three random counting measures which are closed under restriction to a subspace, i.e. closed under Point process operation#Thinning.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] These random measures are examples of the mixed binomial process and share the distributional self-similarity property of the Poisson random measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] They are the only members of the canonical non-negative power series family of distributions to possess this property and include the Poisson distribution, negative binomial distribution, and binomial distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson random measure is independent on disjoint subspaces, whereas the other PT random measures (negative binomial and binomial) have positive and negative covariances.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The PT random measures are discussed and include the Poisson random measure, negative binomial random measure, and binomial random measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, the concept of distance is of practical interest for applications, while topological structure is needed for Palm distributions, meaning that point processes are usually defined on mathematical spaces with metrics.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Furthermore, a realization of a point process can be considered as a counting measure, so points processes are types of random measures known as random counting measures.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] In this context, the Poisson and other point processes have been studied on a locally compact second countable Hausdorff space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] A **Cox point process**, **Cox process** or **doubly stochastic Poisson process** is a generalization of the Poisson point process by letting its intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ to be also random and independent of the underlying Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The process is named after David Cox who introduced it in 1955, though other Poisson processes with random intensities had been independently introduced earlier by Lucien Le Cam and Maurice Quenouille.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The intensity measure may be a realization of random variable or a random field.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if the logarithm of the intensity measure is a Gaussian random field, then the resulting process is known as a *log Gaussian Cox process*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] More generally, the intensity measures is a realization of a non-negative locally finite random measure.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] Cox point processes exhibit a *clustering* of points, which can be shown mathematically to be larger than those of Poisson point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The generality and tractability of Cox processes has resulted in them being used as models in fields such as spatial statistics and wireless networks.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] For a given point process, each random point of a point process can have a random mathematical object, known as a **mark**, randomly assigned to it.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] These marks can be as diverse as integers, real numbers, lines, geometrical objects or other point processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The pair consisting of a point of the point process and its corresponding mark is called a marked point, and all the marked points form a **marked point process**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] It is often assumed that the random marks are independent of each other and identically distributed, yet the mark of a point can still depend on the location of its corresponding point in the underlying (state) space.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If the underlying point process is a Poisson point process, then the resulting point process is a **marked Poisson point process**.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] If a general point process is defined on some mathematical space and the random marks are defined on another mathematical space, then the marked point process is defined on the Cartesian product of these two spaces.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] where $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ is a Borel measurable set.
[src:queueing-theory-math/poisson-point-process-p02] The failure process with the exponential smoothing of intensity functions (FP-ESI) is an extension of the nonhomogeneous Poisson process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing theory has its origins in research by Agner Krarup Erlang, who created models to describe the system of incoming calls at the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange Company.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] These ideas were seminal to the field of teletraffic engineering and have since seen applications in telecommunications, traffic engineering, computing, project management, and particularly industrial engineering, where they are applied in the design of factories, shops, offices, and hospitals.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing theory is one of the major areas of study in the discipline of management science.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Through management science, businesses are able to solve a variety of problems using different scientific and mathematical approaches.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing analysis is the probabilistic analysis of waiting lines, and thus the results, also referred to as the operating characteristics, are probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The overall goal of queueing analysis is to compute these characteristics for the current system and then test several alternatives that could lead to improvement.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Computing the operating characteristics for the current system and comparing the values to the characteristics of the alternative systems allows managers to see the pros and cons of each potential option.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] These systems help in the final decision making process by showing ways to increase savings, reduce waiting time, improve efficiency, etc.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The main queueing models that can be used are the single-server waiting line system and the multiple-server waiting line system, which are discussed further below.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] These models can be further differentiated depending on whether service times are constant or undefined, the queue length is finite, the calling population is finite, etc.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] A *queue* or *queueing node* can be thought of as nearly a black box.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] *Jobs* (also called *customers* or *requests*, depending on the field) arrive to the queue, possibly wait some time, take some time being processed, and then depart from the queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] However, the queueing node is not quite a pure black box since some information is needed about the inside of the queueing node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The queue has one or more *servers* which can each be paired with an arriving job.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] When the job is completed and departs, that server will again be free to be paired with another arriving job.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] An analogy often used is that of the cashier at a supermarket.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Customers arrive, are processed by the cashier, and depart.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Each cashier processes one customer at a time, and hence this is a queueing node with only one server.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] A setting where a customer will leave immediately if the cashier is busy when the customer arrives, is referred to as a queue with no *buffer* (or no *waiting area*).
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] A setting with a waiting zone for up to *n* customers is called a queue with a buffer of size *n*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The behaviour of a single queue (also called a *queueing node*) can be described by a birth–death process, which describes the arrivals and departures from the queue, along with the number of jobs currently in the system.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] If *k* denotes the number of jobs in the system (either being serviced or waiting if the queue has a buffer of waiting jobs), then an arrival increases *k* by 1 and a departure decreases *k* by 1.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The system transitions between values of *k* by *births* and *deaths*, which occur at the arrival rates $\lambda _{i}$ and the departure rates $\mu _{i}$ for each job i .
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] For a queue, these rates are generally considered not to vary with the number of jobs in the queue, so a single average rate of arrivals/departures per unit time is assumed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The steady state equations for the birth-and-death process, known as the balance equations, are as follows.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Here $P_{n}$ denotes the steady state probability to be in state *n*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] which, together with the equation for $P_{n}$ $(n\geq 1)$ , fully describes the required steady state probabilities.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Single queueing nodes are usually described using Kendall's notation in the form A/S/*c* where *A* describes the distribution of durations between each arrival to the queue, *S* the distribution of service times for jobs, and *c* the number of servers at the node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] For an example of the notation, the M/M/1 queue is a simple model where a single server serves jobs that arrive according to a Poisson process (where inter-arrival durations are exponentially distributed) and have exponentially distributed service times (the M denotes a Markov process).
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In an M/G/1 queue, the G stands for *general* and indicates an arbitrary probability distribution for service times.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Further, let $E_{n}$ represent the number of times the system enters state *n*, and $L_{n}$ represent the number of times the system leaves state *n*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] That is, the number of times the system leaves a state differs by at most 1 from the number of times it enters that state, since it will either return into that state at some time in the future ( $E_{n}=L_{n}$ ) or not ( $\left\vert E_{n}-L_{n}\right\vert =1$ ).
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] When the system arrives at a steady state, the arrival rate should be equal to the departure rate.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] A common basic queueing system is attributed to Erlang and is a modification of Little's Law.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Assuming an exponential distribution for the rates, the waiting time *W* can be defined as the proportion of arrivals that are served.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The two-stage one-box model is common in epidemiology.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In 1909, Agner Krarup Erlang, a Danish engineer who worked for the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange, published the first paper on what would now be called queueing theory.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] He modeled the number of telephone calls arriving at an exchange by a Poisson process and solved the M/D/1 queue in 1917 and M/D/*k* queueing model in 1920.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] If the node has more jobs than servers, then jobs will queue and wait for service.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The M/G/1 queue was solved by Felix Pollaczek in 1930, a solution later recast in probabilistic terms by Aleksandr Khinchin and now known as the Pollaczek–Khinchine formula.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] After the 1940s, queueing theory became an area of research interest to mathematicians.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In 1953, David George Kendall solved the GI/M/*k* queue and introduced the modern notation for queues, now known as Kendall's notation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In 1957, Pollaczek studied the GI/G/1 using an integral equation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] John Kingman gave a formula for the mean waiting time in a G/G/1 queue, now known as Kingman's formula.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Leonard Kleinrock worked on the application of queueing theory to message switching in the early 1960s and packet switching in the early 1970s.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] His initial contribution to this field was his doctoral thesis at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1962, published in book form in 1964.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] His theoretical work published in the early 1970s underpinned the use of packet switching in the ARPANET, a forerunner to the Internet.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The matrix geometric method and matrix analytic methods have allowed queues with phase-type distributed inter-arrival and service time distributions to be considered.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Systems with coupled orbits are an important part in queueing theory in the application to wireless networks and signal processing.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Modern day application of queueing theory concerns among other things product development where (material) products have a spatiotemporal existence, in the sense that products have a certain volume and a certain duration.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Problems such as performance metrics for the M/G/*k* queue remain an open problem.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] this principle states that customers are served one at a time and that the customer that has been waiting the longest is served first.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Service capacity is shared equally between customers.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] (ROS), this discipline states that the next job served is selected at random from the jobs waiting in the queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Customers with high priority are served first.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] (where a job in service can be interrupted by a higher-priority job).
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest size.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest original size.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The next job to serve is the one with the smallest remaining processing requirement.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Server failures occur according to a stochastic (random) process (usually Poisson) and are followed by setup periods during which the server is unavailable.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The interrupted customer remains in the service area until server is fixed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Arriving customers not served (either due to the queue having no buffer, or due to balking or reneging by the customer) are also known as *dropouts*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The average rate of dropouts is a significant parameter describing a queue.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queue networks are systems in which multiple queues are connected by *customer routing*.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] When a customer is serviced at one node, it can join another node and queue for service, or leave the network.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] For networks of *m* nodes, the state of the system can be described by an *m*–dimensional vector (*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**m*) where *x**i* represents the number of customers at each node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The simplest non-trivial networks of queues are called tandem queues.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The first significant results in this area were Jackson networks, for which an efficient product-form stationary distribution exists and the mean value analysis (which allows average metrics such as throughput and sojourn times) can be computed.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] If the total number of customers in the network remains constant, the network is called a *closed network* and has been shown to also have a product–form stationary distribution by the Gordon–Newell theorem.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] This result was extended to the BCMP network, where a network with very general service time, regimes, and customer routing is shown to also exhibit a product–form stationary distribution.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The normalizing constant can be calculated with the Buzen's algorithm, proposed in 1973.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Networks of customers have also been investigated, such as Kelly networks, where customers of different classes experience different priority levels at different service nodes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Another type of network are G-networks, first proposed by Erol Gelenbe in 1993: these networks do not assume exponential time distributions like the classic Jackson network.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In discrete-time networks where there is a constraint on which service nodes can be active at any time, the max-weight scheduling algorithm chooses a service policy to give optimal throughput in the case that each job visits only a single-person service node.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In the more general case where jobs can visit more than one node, backpressure routing gives optimal throughput.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] A network scheduler must choose a queueing algorithm, which affects the characteristics of the larger network.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Mean-field models consider the limiting behaviour of the empirical measure (proportion of queues in different states) as the number of queues *m* approaches infinity.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The impact of other queues on any given queue in the network is approximated by a differential equation.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The deterministic model converges to the same stationary distribution as the original model.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In a system with high occupancy rates (utilisation near 1), a heavy traffic approximation can be used to approximate the queueing length process by a reflected Brownian motion, Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, or more general diffusion process.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The number of dimensions of the Brownian process is equal to the number of queueing nodes, with the diffusion restricted to the non-negative orthant.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Fluid models are continuous deterministic analogs of queueing networks obtained by taking the limit when the process is scaled in time and space, allowing heterogeneous objects.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] This scaled trajectory converges to a deterministic equation which allows the stability of the system to be proven.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] It is known that a queueing network can be stable but have an unstable fluid limit.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing theory finds widespread application in computer science and information technology.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] In networking, for instance, queues are integral to routers and switches, where packets queue up for transmission.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] By applying queueing theory principles, designers can optimize these systems, ensuring responsive performance and efficient resource utilization.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Beyond the technological realm, queueing theory is relevant to everyday experiences.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Whether waiting in line at a supermarket or for public transportation, understanding the principles of queueing theory provides valuable insights into optimizing these systems for enhanced user satisfaction.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] At some point, everyone will be involved in an aspect of queuing.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] What some may view to be an inconvenience could possibly be the most effective method.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing theory, a discipline rooted in applied mathematics and computer science, is a field dedicated to the study and analysis of queues, or waiting lines, and their implications across a diverse range of applications.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] This theoretical framework has proven instrumental in understanding and optimizing the efficiency of systems characterized by the presence of queues.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The study of queues is essential in contexts such as traffic systems, computer networks, telecommunications, and service operations.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] Queueing theory delves into various foundational concepts, with the arrival process and service process being central.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The arrival process describes the manner in which entities join the queue over time, often modeled using stochastic processes like Poisson processes.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] The efficiency of queueing systems is gauged through key performance metrics.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] These include the average queue length, average wait time, and system throughput.
[src:queueing-theory-math/queueing-theory] These metrics provide insights into the system's functionality, guiding decisions aimed at enhancing performance and reducing wait times.
